{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Reliability</strong> standardizes <strong>mechanism failure recovery</strong> — what
    happens when an operation fails (network timeout, server error, database unreachable, computation
    crash) and the system must decide whether to retry, queue, escalate, or surface the failure to the
    user. It defines the contract (via the <a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability Intent</a>), a
    shared <a href="/plugs/customrecoveryhandlerregistry/">recovery handler registry</a> that any
    consumer delegates to, and the
    <a href="#protocol-error-recovery">Error Recovery Protocol</a> that conformant implementations satisfy.
  </p>
  <p>
    Recovery handlers are <strong>pluggable and ordered</strong>: the first registered handler that
    accepts an error owns the recovery. HTTP retry, circuit breaking, offline queuing, and custom
    domain-specific strategies are all equal participants — registered by the application, not hardwired
    into the standard.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">Reliability vs. Validation</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <strong>Reliability</strong> handles <em>system failures</em> — the operation itself broke (timeout,
      crash, network unreachable). The user's input was valid; the mechanism failed.
      <strong><a href="/projects/webvalidation/">Validation</a></strong> handles <em>input invalidity</em> —
      the user provided incorrect data. Never conflate the two: a uniqueness check timing out is a
      Reliability error; the email already being taken is a Validation error.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{{ pc.standardSection('id="features"') }}
  <h3 id="feature-surface">Feature Surface</h3>
  <p>
    What a reliability standard covers, and how each capability is fulfilled.
    <strong>Built-in</strong> = provided by a conformant handler implementation;
    <strong>Compose</strong> = deferred to an existing Web Everything standard.
  </p>
  <div style="overflow-x: auto; max-width: 100%;">
    <we-data-table><table style="min-width: 680px;">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Applies To</th><th>What it does</th><th>Built-in</th><th>Compose</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td colspan="5" style="font-weight:600; background:rgba(5,150,105,0.06);">Retry</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Automatic retry</strong></td><td>Any operation</td><td>Silent retry without user interaction</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Backoff strategy</strong></td><td>Any operation</td><td>Immediate, linear, or exponential delay between attempts</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Manual retry</strong></td><td>Any operation</td><td>User-triggered retry affordance</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Max attempts</strong></td><td>Any operation</td><td>Cap on retry count before escalating</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td colspan="5" style="font-weight:600; background:rgba(5,150,105,0.06);">Resilience patterns</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Circuit breaker</strong></td><td>Any endpoint / service</td><td>Stop retrying after consecutive failures; probe to recover</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Offline queuing</strong></td><td>Network operations</td><td>Queue operations when offline; replay on reconnection</td><td>✅ handler</td><td>—</td></tr>
