{{ pc.standardSection('id="how"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h3>
  <p>
    A consumer (Resource Loader, form submission handler, background task) never contains retry logic.
    It catches a failure, resolves the registry through the injector chain, and delegates:
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// 1. Register handlers at application bootstrap (priority order).
import { HttpRetryHandler } from '@web-reliability/http';
import { CircuitBreakerHandler } from '@web-reliability/circuit-breaker';
import { OfflineQueueHandler } from '@web-reliability/offline-queue';

customRecovery.define('offline-queue', new OfflineQueueHandler());
customRecovery.define('circuit-breaker', new CircuitBreakerHandler({ threshold: 5 }));
customRecovery.define('http-retry', new HttpRetryHandler({ strategy: 'exponential', maxRetries: 3 }));

// 2. Any consumer delegates on failure — it never knows which handler ran.
async function loadWithRecovery(context: RecoveryContext): Promise<void> {
  const registry = customRecovery; // resolved via injector chain
  for (const handler of registry.values()) {
    const result = await handler.tryRecover(context.error, context);
    if (result) return applyResult(result);
  }
  // No handler accepted — surface the error.
  throw context.error;
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> the <a href="/plugs/customrecoveryhandler/"><code>CustomRecoveryHandler</code></a> interface — <code>tryRecover(error, context): Promise&lt;RecoveryResult | null&gt;</code> — satisfied by every handler alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <a href="/plugs/customrecoveryhandlerregistry/"><code>CustomRecoveryHandlerRegistry</code></a> (<code>window.customRecovery</code>) holds handlers in priority order.</li>
    <li><strong>First that accepts wins:</strong> returning <code>null</code> declines without side effects; the next handler is tried. Registration order is the priority — explicit and reviewable.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-error-recovery"') }}
  <h3 id="error-recovery-protocol">Error Recovery Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for handling mechanism failures through pluggable recovery handlers.
    Defines the <a href="/plugs/customrecoveryhandler/"><code>CustomRecoveryHandler</code></a> contract,
    the <a href="/plugs/customrecoveryhandlerregistry/"><code>CustomRecoveryHandlerRegistry</code></a>
    resolution pattern, and the observable states any conformant consumer must satisfy. Applies to
    <strong>any mechanism failure</strong> — HTTP errors, database timeouts, computation crashes,
    async task failures — not only resource loading. The protocol never prescribes which recovery
    strategy to apply; that is the registered handler's decision.
  </p>

  <h4 id="scope-mechanism-failure">Scope: Mechanism Failure Only</h4>
  <p>The Error Recovery Protocol is strictly for <strong>operation / system failure</strong>. Do not conflate with input validation:</p>
  <we-data-table><table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Domain</th><th>Failure Kind</th><th>Example</th><th>Owned By</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Reliability</strong></td>
        <td>Mechanism failure</td>
        <td>Uniqueness check timed out; server unreachable; async validator crashed</td>
        <td>Error Recovery Protocol</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Validation</strong></td>
        <td>Input invalidity</td>
        <td>Email already taken; password too short; field missing</td>
        <td><a href="/projects/webvalidation/#protocol-validation">Validation Protocol</a></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></we-data-table>

  <h4 id="consumer-pattern">How Consumers Use the Registry</h4>
  <p>
    A conformant consumer (Resource Loader, form submission handler, background task) must
    <strong>never contain recovery logic</strong>. On failure it resolves
    <code>CustomRecoveryHandlerRegistry</code> and delegates:
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Conformant consumer pattern.
async function runWithRecovery(
    operation: () => Promise<void>,
    context: RecoveryContext,
): Promise<void> {
    const registry = /* resolve customRecovery from injector chain */;

    for (const handler of registry.values()) {
        const result = await handler.tryRecover(context.error, context);
        if (result === null) continue;   // Handler declined — try next.

        if (result.outcome === 'retry') {
            if (result.delay) await sleep(result.delay);
            return runWithRecovery(operation, { ...context, attempt: context.attempt + 1 });
        }
        if (result.outcome === 'queued') return;   // Handler owns replay.
        if (result.outcome === 'fallback') throw new FallbackSignal(context.error);
        if (result.outcome === 'abort') throw context.error;
    }

    // No handler accepted — surface the error.
    throw context.error;
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="observable-states">Observable States</h4>
  <p>A conformant consumer must reflect these states to the <a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability Intent</a> UX dimensions:</p>
  <we-data-table><table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>State</th><th>Condition</th><th>Reliability Intent Dimension</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>recovering</code></td>
        <td>A retry or queue result is pending; the operation is in flight or waiting. The <code>RecoveryResult.phase</code> discriminator (#1032 Fork&nbsp;2) refines <em>which</em> in-flight phase: <code>retrying</code> / <code>queued</code> / <code>awaiting-manual</code> (core) + registered extensions (e.g. <code>circuit-open</code>)</td>
        <td><code>recovery: automatic | manual</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>fallback</code></td>
        <td>All handlers declined, or a handler returned <code>outcome: 'fallback'</code></td>
        <td><code>fallback: skeleton | empty | previous</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>failed</code></td>
        <td>A handler returned <code>outcome: 'abort'</code> or no handler accepted</td>
        <td><code>tolerance: terminal</code></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></we-data-table>

  <h4 id="web-standards-alignment">Web Standards Alignment</h4>
  <we-data-table><table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/AbortController">AbortController</a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td>Each recovery attempt receives a fresh <code>AbortSignal</code>. The consumer aborts the previous attempt's signal before dispatching the next. Handlers may surface this signal to the underlying operation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Navigator/onLine">navigator.onLine</a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td>Available to handlers for offline detection. Not mandated — handlers opt in as needed.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/unhandledrejection_event">Unhandled Rejection</a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td><code>RecoveryContext.error</code> carries the raw <code>Error</code> from any rejected promise. Handlers inspect it to determine whether they accept the failure.</td>
    </tr>
  </table></we-data-table>

  <h4 id="interface">Interface</h4>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
/** Outcome the handler instructs the consumer to apply. */
type RecoveryOutcome = 'retry' | 'queued' | 'fallback' | 'abort';

/** #1032 Fork 1 — normalized recoverability (the UX-facing projection of
 *  the handler's PRIVATE classification). Orthogonal to the Reliability
 *  Intent `tolerance` axis (recoverability × severity — not 1:1). */
type FailureDisposition = 'transient' | 'terminal' | 'deferred';

/** #1032 Fork 2 — in-flight recovery phase. Open meta-schema: a minimal
 *  core, widened by REGISTERED extensions without a contract break. */
type RecoveryPhaseCore = 'retrying' | 'queued' | 'awaiting-manual';
type RecoveryPhase     = RecoveryPhaseCore | (string & {}); // e.g. 'circuit-open' (registered extension)

/** Returned when a handler accepts the error. */
interface RecoveryResult {
    outcome: RecoveryOutcome;
    disposition?: FailureDisposition; // #1032 — what kind of failure it was.
    phase?: RecoveryPhase;            // #1032 — which in-flight recovery phase to surface.
    delay?: number;       // ms before retry (outcome: 'retry' only).
    signal?: AbortSignal; // Fresh signal for the next attempt.
}

/** Passed to every handler during resolution. */
interface RecoveryContext {
    error: Error;
    attempt: number;       // 1-based; increments on each retry.
    signal: AbortSignal;   // Signal of the most recent attempt.
    operation?: string;    // Opaque identifier for the failing operation.
}

/** Contract every handler implements.
 *  Return RecoveryResult to own the recovery; return null to decline. */
abstract class CustomRecoveryHandler {
    abstract tryRecover(
        error: Error,
        context: RecoveryContext,
    ): Promise<RecoveryResult | null>;
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="design-decisions">Design Decisions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Registry, not chain:</strong> recovery delegates to handlers held by <code>CustomRecoveryHandlerRegistry</code> rather than a purpose-built chain object. <code>registry.values()</code> already provides ordered iteration; a dedicated chain would duplicate it. Registration order is priority — explicit and reviewable.</li>
    <li><strong>First-that-accepts:</strong> handlers are tried in registration order. The first <code>tryRecover()</code> that returns a non-null <code>RecoveryResult</code> owns the recovery; subsequent handlers are not called. Mirrors the pattern used by <code>CustomExpressionParserRegistry</code> (<code>tryParse</code>) and route matching (<code>matchRoute</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>No default handlers:</strong> the protocol ships no built-in handlers. Implementations (HTTP retry, circuit breaker, offline queue) are registered by the consuming project — keeps the standard lean and prevents prescribing strategies that may not suit every operation type.</li>
    <li><strong>Null means pass-through:</strong> a handler returning <code>null</code> explicitly declines the error without side effects. Avoids the need for a separate <code>canHandle()</code> predicate.</li>
    <li><strong>Composition is an author-ordered composite handler, not protocol orchestration (#1032 Fork&nbsp;3):</strong> single-dispatch is preserved — the registry still picks the <em>first</em> handler that accepts. Multi-concern cooperation (breaker × retry × offline) is a composite handler the author <em>wraps in the order they need</em> (the Polly <code>PolicyWrap</code> analogue), since the wrap order is load-bearing: <code>new CircuitBreakerHandler(new RetryHandler(httpRetry))</code> counts a whole retried attempt as one breaker call (correct for short delays); wrap the other way for long delays. A flat-escalation <code>'continue'</code> outcome is <strong>not</strong> in the contract — it expresses only flat fallthrough, never this nesting, so it's a <em>deferred, app-opt-in</em> capability (added additively when a real app needs flat escalation), not a rejected branch.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="exports">Exports</h4>
  <we-data-table><table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Export</th><th>Kind</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>RecoveryHandler</code></td><td>Abstract Class</td><td>Base contract all handlers extend</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>RecoveryContext</code></td><td>Interface</td><td>Error, attempt count, abort signal passed to handlers</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>RecoveryResult</code></td><td>Interface</td><td>Outcome returned by an accepting handler</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>RecoveryOutcome</code></td><td>Type</td><td><code>'retry' | 'queued' | 'fallback' | 'abort'</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>FailureDisposition</code></td><td>Type</td><td>#1032 Fork&nbsp;1 — <code>'transient' | 'terminal' | 'deferred'</code> (normalized recoverability)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>RecoveryPhase</code></td><td>Type</td><td>#1032 Fork&nbsp;2 — open meta-schema; core <code>'retrying' | 'queued' | 'awaiting-manual'</code> + registered extensions</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></we-data-table>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Reliability owns <em>whether and how to retry</em>, not <em>how loading states are shown</em> or
    <em>what replaces failed content</em> — those compose with neighbouring standards:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability Intent</a></strong> — the declarative UX protocol; tolerance, recovery, and fallback dimensions consumed by components to configure their recovery UX.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a></strong> — loading-state UX (skeleton, overlay, stale) shown by Resource Loader during retry attempts.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/blocks/resource-loader/">Resource Loader</a></strong> — primary consumer; delegates failure handling to the registry rather than containing retry logic itself.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Reliability is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The contract and handler registry are specified
    via the <a href="#protocol-error-recovery">Error Recovery Protocol</a>; concrete handler
    implementations (HTTP retry, circuit breaker, offline queue) are the first planned implementations.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Should <code>RecoveryContext</code> carry an attempt counter, or is that the handler's internal concern?</li>
    <li>Is a cancellation hook (<code>RecoveryResult.abort()</code>) needed, or is AbortSignal sufficient?</li>
  </ul>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <strong>Resolved (#1032 Fork&nbsp;2):</strong> Resource Loader surfaces the active recovery state via the
    <code>RecoveryPhase</code> discriminator on the in-flight <code>recovering</code> state — an open meta-schema
    with a minimal core (<code>retrying</code> / <code>queued</code> / <code>awaiting-manual</code>). <code>circuit-open</code>
    is a <strong>registered extension</strong>, not a core member, because the protocol bundles no
    circuit-breaker handler. Kept separate from data/loader status (the TanStack <code>status</code> vs
    <code>fetchStatus</code> split); the Loader Intent UX binds to the phase it understands and treats unknown
    phases as generic <code>recovering</code>.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
